{{about|external censorship of the iTunes Store|censorship carried out by Apple|Censorship by Apple}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}
'''Censorship of the iTunes Store''' refers to external attempts at blocking access to digital content distributed through the [[iTunes Store]].

==Australia==
{{see also|Censorship in Australia}}
In 2010, the [[Australian Labor Party]] announced its intent to subject the 220,000 mobile apps available on the Australia App Store to [[Australian Classification Board]] regulations, which require that developers pay evaluation fees ranging from $470 to $2040.<ref name='Bodey 2010-08-16'>{{cite news | first = Michael | last = Bodey | title = Apps and games to face censor, says ALP | date = 16 August 2010 | url = http://www.theaustralian.com.au/media/apps-and-games-to-face-censor-says-alp/story-e6frg996-1225905609780 | work = The Australian | accessdate = 2013-06-02}}</ref> A 2011 article in the ''[[Sydney Morning Herald]]'' clarified that "Australians will soon be able to complain about mobile game apps they take offence to and get them removed from app stores such as Apple's iTunes if they're deemed 'refused classification'. And if mobile game apps are classified anything above MA15+ and the government doesn't introduce an R18+ games classification (which it plans to vote on in July), then any game app rated over MA15+ will also be refused classification." Sentiments were also expressed over other apps: "What is unclear, however, is how the Classification Board will classify apps that aren't necessarily games like [[Grindr]], an app for gay users which uses [GPS] to find nearby males".<ref name='SMH 2011-03-09'>{{cite news | first = Ben | last = Grubb | title = Government to censor iTunes app store | date = 9 March 2011 | url = http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/smartphone-apps/government-to-censor-itunes-app-store-20110309-1bng2.html | work = The Sydney Morning Herald | accessdate = 2013-06-02}}</ref>

==China==
{{See also|Internet censorship in the People's Republic of China}}

The China App Store was affected by connection-level censorship until an unknown point in time when [[Apple Inc|Apple]] enabled a [[HTTPS]]-by-default configuration.<ref name='Muncaster 2012-12-21'>{{cite news | first = Phil | last = Muncaster | title = Apple shifts iTunes to HTTPS, sidesteps China's censors | date = 21 December 2012 | url = https://www.theregister.co.uk/2012/12/21/itunes_https_shift_routes_around_great_firewall/ | work = The Register | accessdate = 2013-06-02}}</ref> Searches for '[[Virtual Private Network|VPN]]', for example, would cause the connection to be reset.<ref name='Muncaster 2012-12-21'/>

According to the ''[[Global Times]]'', the [[Ministry of Industry and Information Technology of the People's Republic of China|Ministry of Industry and Information Technology]] said on 13 December 2012 that it planned to "strengthen regulation of China's mobile applications market" in the near future.<ref name='GT 2012-12-13'>{{cite news | first = Chen | last = Yang | title = MIIT to tighten app regulations | date = 13 December 2012 | publisher = ''[[People's Daily]]'' | url = http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/750131.shtml | work = Global Times | accessdate = 2013-06-02}}</ref> The Shanghai-based ''IT Times'' quoted [[Chen Jinqiao]] as saying that the plans included "[bringing] app developers under supervision and [establishing] a real-name registration system for independent developers.<ref name='GT 2012-12-13'/>

In 2013, Apple pulled several apps from the China App Store for containing [[Book censorship in China|books banned by the government]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-04-04/apple-pulls-bookstore-app-in-china-over-illegal-content-ft-says|title=Apple Pulls Bookstore App in China Over Illegal Content, FT Says|website=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2016-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/39e02d6c-9d02-11e2-88e9-00144feabdc0.html|title=Apple bars China app for ‘illegal’ content|last=Anderlini|first=Jamil|date=4 April 2013|newspaper=Financial Times|issn=0307-1766|access-date=2016-04-22}}</ref> Several apps enabling users to bypass the [[Great Firewall]] and access restricted sites in China were also removed later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/10/04/tech/opendoor-app-apple-china/index.html|title=Apple slammed in China for pulling firewall-busting app OpenDoor - CNN.com|last=CNN|first=By Tim Hume and Feng Ke|website=CNN|access-date=2016-04-22}}</ref> The [[News (Apple)|Apple News application]] bundled with iOS 9 is disabled in China for all users as well, of which all contents, including the articles already downloaded to the device, are not available to read in China.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/apple-disabled-the-apple-news-app-in-china-2015-10|title=Apple has disabled the Apple News app in China|website=Business Insider|access-date=2016-04-22}}</ref>

Apple's [[iBooks]] and iTunes Movies, available in China since September 2015, were both shut down in China in April 2016, less than seven months after the launch.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/pr/library/2015/09/30Apple-Brings-Apple-Music-iTunes-Movies-iBooks-to-Customers-in-China-Starting-Today.html|title=Apple – Press Info – Apple Brings Apple Music, iTunes Movies & iBooks to Customers in China Starting Today|website=www.apple.com|access-date=2016-04-22}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/apples-ibooks-store-and-itunes-movie-services-go-dark-in-china-2016-4|title=Apple's iBooks store and iTunes movie services go dark in China|website=Business Insider|access-date=2016-04-22}}</ref> The services were disabled by the [[State Administration of Press, Publication, Radio, Film and Television]] of China after the authority introduced regulations imposing strict curbs on online publishing, particularly for foreign firms.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/22/technology/apple-no-longer-immune-to-chinas-scrutiny-of-us-tech-firms.html|title=Apple No Longer Immune to China's Scrutiny of U.S. Tech Firms|last=Mozur|first=Paul|date=21 April 2016|last2=Perlez|first2=Jane|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/04/21/apples-itunes-movies-ibooks-store-reportedly-shut-down-in-china/|title=Apple's iTunes Movies, iBooks Store reportedly shut down in China|website=VentureBeat|access-date=2016-04-22}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.businesstimes.com.sg/technology/apple-says-itunes-movies-ibooks-services-closed-down-in-china|title=Apple says iTunes Movies, iBooks services closed down in China|website=The Business Times|access-date=2016-04-22}}</ref> Apple said in response that they hope to restore the services in China "as soon as possible".<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1"/>

